2026-04-16 12:11:53 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['load‑module series diode'] hypothesis_explanation='All three modules see correct supply: with 12 V applied and the switch ON, the power‑supply output, the control‑module input, and the load‑module input each have about 12 V between their ‘+’ and ‘−’ lines, and all positive lines are at the same potential. Thus the inter‑module cabling and polarity are correct, and the control‑module red “inverted cables” LED stays OFF as expected. The power‑supply green LED being ON confirms the source is healthy.\n\nThe only remaining series element in the path to the lamp is the diode in the load module (in series with both the indicator and main lamp). With correct polarity present at the load‑module input and the switch closed, the main lamp and internal indicator should both light if that diode conducts. Since neither lamp lights while full supply is present at the load module terminals, the most plausible single fault is that the series diode in the load module is open‑circuit (or otherwise failed non‑conducting) even in the forward direction. Replacing/repairing the load‑module series diode should restore operation.'
